column2: {'TERM': 'Python', 'MEANING': 'A high-level programming language known for its simplicity and readability.'}
{'TERM': 'Software', 'MEANING': 'Programs and applications that run on computers or other devices.'}
{'TERM': 'Development', 'MEANING': 'The process of creating or improving software products.'}
{'TERM': 'Programming', 'MEANING': 'The act of writing and designing computer programs.'}
{'TERM': 'Language', 'MEANING': 'A system of communication used to express instructions to a computer.'}
{'TERM': 'System', 'MEANING': 'A collection of elements or components working together to perform a task or function.'}
{'TERM': 'Application', 'MEANING': 'A software program designed to perform a specific task or set of tasks for the user.'}
{'TERM': 'Framework', 'MEANING': 'A pre-built structure or platform that provides a foundation for developing software applications.'}
{'TERM': 'Library', 'MEANING': 'A collection of pre-written code or functions that can be reused in software development.'}
{'TERM': 'Module', 'MEANING': 'A self-contained unit of code that can be used and reused in various programs.'}
{'TERM': 'Function', 'MEANING': 'A named block of code that performs a specific task or operation.'}
{'TERM': 'Variable', 'MEANING': 'A named storage location in computer memory used to hold data.'}
{'TERM': 'Object', 'MEANING': 'An instance of a class in object-oriented programming, encapsulating data and behavior.'}
{'TERM': 'Class', 'MEANING': 'A blueprint for creating objects, providing initial values and methods.'}
{'TERM': 'Method', 'MEANING': 'A function associated with a class, typically acting on its instances.'}
{'TERM': 'Statement', 'MEANING': 'A unit of code that expresses some action to be carried out.'}
{'TERM': 'Syntax', 'MEANING': 'The rules that define the structure of a programming language.'}
{'TERM': 'Algorithm', 'MEANING': 'A step-by-step procedure for solving a problem or accomplishing a task.'}
{'TERM': 'Debugging', 'MEANING': 'The process of finding and fixing errors or bugs in software code.'}
{'TERM': 'Testing', 'MEANING': 'The process of evaluating a software application or system to find defects and ensure its quality.'}
{'TERM': 'Documentation', 'MEANING': 'Written information describing the functionality and use of software or hardware.'}
{'TERM': 'Version', 'MEANING': 'A specific iteration or release of a software product.'}
{'TERM': 'Repository', 'MEANING': 'A storage location where software code and related assets are stored and managed.'}
{'TERM': 'Merge', 'MEANING': 'Combining changes from different branches of code into a single codebase.'}
{'TERM': 'Commit', 'MEANING': 'A record of changes made to a repository, typically accompanied by a message describing the changes.'}
{'TERM': 'Branch', 'MEANING': 'A separate line of development in a version control system, allowing for parallel work on code.'}
{'TERM': 'Clone', 'MEANING': 'Creating a copy of a repository or branch.'}
{'TERM': 'Pull', 'MEANING': 'Fetching and integrating changes from a remote repository into a local branch.'}
{'TERM': 'Push', 'MEANING': 'Uploading local changes to a remote repository.'}
{'TERM': 'Merge Conflict', 'MEANING': 'A situation where two branches of code have changes that cannot be automatically reconciled.'}
{'TERM': 'API', 'MEANING': 'Application Programming Interface; a set of rules and protocols for building and interacting with software applications.'}
{'TERM': 'Interface', 'MEANING': 'A boundary across which two independent systems meet and interact.'}
{'TERM': 'GUI', 'MEANING': 'Graphical User Interface; a visual way of interacting with software using graphical elements.'}
{'TERM': 'CLI', 'MEANING': 'Command Line Interface; a text-based way of interacting with software using command-line commands.'}
{'TERM': 'IDE', 'MEANING': 'Integrated Development Environment; a software application that provides comprehensive facilities to computer programmers for software development.'}
{'TERM': 'Debugger', 'MEANING': 'A tool used to identify and remove errors or bugs from software code.'}
{'TERM': 'Compiler', 'MEANING': 'A program that translates code written in a high-level programming language into machine code.'}
{'TERM': 'Interpreter', 'MEANING': 'A program that directly executes instructions written in a programming language without the need for prior compilation.'}
{'TERM': 'Syntax Error', 'MEANING': 'An error that occurs when code violates the rules of the programming language.'}
{'TERM': 'Exception', 'MEANING': 'An error or unexpected condition that occurs during the execution of a program.'}
{'TERM': 'Recursion', 'MEANING': 'A programming technique where a function calls itself in its definition.'}
{'TERM': 'Loop', 'MEANING': 'A control flow statement that allows code to be executed repeatedly based on a condition.'}
{'TERM': 'Array', 'MEANING': 'A data structure that stores a collection of elements, typically of the same type.'}
{'TERM': 'List', 'MEANING': 'A data structure that stores a collection of elements in a specific order.'}
{'TERM': 'Tuple', 'MEANING': 'A data structure that stores an ordered collection of elements, which cannot be modified after creation.'}
{'TERM': 'Dictionary', 'MEANING': 'A data structure that stores a collection of key-value pairs, allowing fast retrieval of values based on their keys.'}
{'TERM': 'Set', 'MEANING': 'A data structure that stores a collection of unique elements, without any particular order.'}
{'TERM': 'Stack', 'MEANING': 'A data structure that follows the Last In, First Out (LIFO) principle, where elements are added and removed from the same end.'}
{'TERM': 'Queue', 'MEANING': 'A data structure that follows the First In, First Out (FIFO) principle, where elements are added at the rear and removed from the front.'}
{'TERM': 'Heap', 'MEANING': 'A specialized tree-based data structure that satisfies the heap property.'}
{'TERM': 'Binary Tree', 'MEANING': 'A tree data structure in which each node has at most two children.'}
{'TERM': 'Graph', 'MEANING': 'A data structure consisting of a set of nodes and a set of edges that connect pairs of nodes.'}
{'TERM': 'Sorting', 'MEANING': 'The process of arranging elements in a specific order.'}
{'TERM': 'Searching', 'MEANING': 'The process of finding a specific element within a collection of elements.'}
{'TERM': 'Big O Notation', 'MEANING': 'A mathematical notation that describes the limiting behavior of a function when the argument approaches a particular value or infinity.'}
{'TERM': 'Complexity', 'MEANING': 'The measure of how the runtime of an algorithm or function increases with the size of its input.'}
{'TERM': 'Asymptotic', 'MEANING': 'Relating to the behavior of a function as the input size approaches infinity.'}
{'TERM': 'Efficiency', 'MEANING': 'The ability to accomplish a task with minimal wasted time, effort, or resources.'}
{'TERM': 'Optimization', 'MEANING': 'The process of making a system, design, or code as efficient as possible.'}
{'TERM': 'Agile', 'MEANING': 'A software development methodology focused on iterative development, collaboration, and customer feedback.'}
{'TERM': 'Scrum', 'MEANING': 'A framework within the Agile methodology that emphasizes teamwork, accountability, and iterative progress.'}
{'TERM': 'Kanban', 'MEANING': 'A method for managing knowledge work with an emphasis on just-in-time delivery while not overloading the team members.'}
{'TERM': 'Git', 'MEANING': 'A distributed version control system for tracking changes in source code during software development.'}
{'TERM': 'GitHub', 'MEANING': 'A web-based hosting service for version control using Git.'}
{'TERM': 'Bitbucket', 'MEANING': 'A web-based hosting service for projects that use either the Mercurial or Git revision control systems.'}
{'TERM': 'Continuous Integration', 'MEANING': 'The practice of frequently integrating code changes into a shared repository, followed by an automated build and test process.'}
{'TERM': 'Continuous Deployment', 'MEANING': 'The practice of automatically deploying code changes to production environments after passing automated tests.'}
{'TERM': 'Containerization', 'MEANING': 'The process of encapsulating an application and its dependencies into a container that can run on any computing environment.'}
{'TERM': 'Virtualization', 'MEANING': 'The process of creating a virtual representation of a physical computing device, such as a server, storage device, or network resource.'}
{'TERM': 'Cloud Computing', 'MEANING': 'The delivery of computing services—including servers, storage, databases, networking, software, and analytics—over the internet.'}
{'TERM': 'Microservices', 'MEANING': 'An architectural style that structures an application as a collection of loosely coupled services, which are independently deployable and scalable.'}
{'TERM': 'RESTful', 'MEANING': 'Representational State Transfer; an architectural style for designing networked applications, emphasizing stateless communication and uniform resource interfaces.'}
{'TERM': 'JSON', 'MEANING': 'JavaScript Object Notation; a lightweight data interchange format.'}
{'TERM': 'XML', 'MEANING': 'eXtensible Markup Language; a markup language that defines a set of rules for encoding documents in a format that is both human-readable and machine-readable.'}
{'TERM': 'HTTP', 'MEANING': 'Hypertext Transfer Protocol; the foundation of data communication for the World Wide Web.'}
{'TERM': 'HTTPS', 'MEANING': 'Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure; an extension of HTTP that provides secure communication over a computer network.'}
{'TERM': 'TCP/IP', 'MEANING': 'Transmission Control Protocol/Internet Protocol; the basic communication language or protocol of the internet.'}
{'TERM': 'SSL', 'MEANING': 'Secure Sockets Layer; a standard security technology for establishing an encrypted link between a server and a client.'}
{'TERM': 'SSH', 'MEANING': 'Secure Shell; a cryptographic network protocol for operating network services securely over an unsecured network.'}
{'TERM': 'DNS', 'MEANING': 'Domain Name System; a hierarchical decentralized naming system for computers, services, or other resources connected to the internet or a private network.'}
{'TERM': 'URL', 'MEANING': 'Uniform Resource Locator; a reference to a web resource that specifies its location on a computer network and the mechanism for retrieving it.'}
{'TERM': 'SQL', 'MEANING': 'Structured Query Language; a domain-specific language used in programming and designed for managing data held in a relational database management system.'}
{'TERM': 'NoSQL', 'MEANING': 'Not Only SQL; a broad class of database management systems that differ from the classic relational database management system.'}
{'TERM': 'ORM', 'MEANING': 'Object-Relational Mapping; a programming technique for converting data between incompatible type systems using object-oriented programming languages.'}
{'TERM': 'CRUD', 'MEANING': 'Create, Read, Update, Delete; a set of basic operations for persistent storage in a database or file system.'}
{'TERM': 'MVC', 'MEANING': 'Model-View-Controller; a software design pattern for implementing user interfaces.'}
